04372nam a22005655i 9780822387565DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223875657 a10.1515/97808223875652doi  a(DE-B1597)553209  a(OCoLC)1224278345  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aN7630 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a760/.044281 aBuszek, Maria Elena, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPin-Up Grrrls :bFeminism, Sexuality, Popular Culture /cMaria Elena Buszek. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b103 photographs (incl. 9 in color)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Defining/Defending the ''Feminist Pin-Up'' -- t1. Representing ''Awarishness'': The Theatrical Origins of the Feminist Pin-Up Girl -- t2. NewWomen for the New Century: Feminism and the Pin-Up at the Fin de Siècle -- t3. The Return of Theatrical Feminism: Early-Twentieth-Century Pin-Ups on the Stage, Street, and Screen -- t4. Celebrating the ''Kind of Girl Who Dominates'': Film Fanzines and the Feminist Pin-Up -- t5. New Frontiers: Sex,Women, and World War II -- t6. Pop Goes the Pin-Up: New Roles and Readings in the Postwar Era -- t7. Our Bodies/Ourselves: Pin-Ups in the Wake of Women's Liberation -- t8. FromWomyn to Grrrls: The Postmodern Feminist Pin-Up -- tConclusion/Commencement -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSubverting stereotypical images of women, a new generation of feminist artists is remaking the pin-up, much as Annie Sprinkle, Cindy Sherman, and others did in the 1970s and 1980s. As shocking as contemporary feminist pin-ups are intended to be, perhaps more surprising is that the pin-up has been appropriated by women for their own empowerment since its inception more than a century ago. Pin-Up Grrrls tells the history of the pin-up from its birth, revealing how its development is intimately connected to the history of feminism. Maria Elena Buszek documents the genre's 150-year history with more than 100 illustrations, many never before published.Beginning with the pin-up's origins in mid-nineteenth-century carte-de-visite photographs of burlesque performers, Buszek explores how female sex symbols, including Adah Isaacs Menken and Lydia Thompson, fought to exert control over their own images. Buszek analyzes the evolution of the pin-up through the advent of the New Woman, the suffrage movement, fanzine photographs of early film stars, the Varga Girl illustrations that appeared in Esquire during World War II, the early years of Playboy magazine, and the recent revival of the genre in appropriations by third-wave feminist artists. A fascinating combination of art history and cultural history, Pin-Up Grrrls is the story of how women have publicly defined and represented their sexuality since the 1860s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aFeminism and art. 0aFeminism in art. 0aPinup art. 0aWomen in art. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822387565zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822387565423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822387565.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles